{
  "answer": "**The Falsafa corpus does not contain a discussion of the concept of *ekam* (the One) in the Old Javanese (Kawi) *tattva* texts.**\n\nThese texts—*Gaṇapatitattva*, *San Hyan Tattvajnana*, *San Hyan Mahajnana*, and *Vṛhaspatitattva*—are Śaiva philosophical works that systematically enumerate and describe the 36 *tattvas* (principles of reality), emphasizing a hierarchical cosmology from the highest *Śivatattva* (conscious, all-pervading divine reality) down to the gross elements. While they explore unity in contexts like the oneness of breath in yoga (*Gaṇapatitattva*), the unification of teaching (*San Hyan Tattvajnana*), or the pervasive *Śivatattva* underlying all (*Vṛhaspatitattva*), there is no explicit reference to *ekam* or an Upanishadic-style \"the One\" as a singular, non-dual absolute.\n\nThe highest realities are framed as *Paramaśivatattva* (formless, infinite Śiva), *Sadāśivatattva* (active, omniscient Śiva with four powers), and *Śivatattva* (pure consciousness pervading *māyā*), rather than a monistic *ekam*. If your query draws from Sanskrit Vedānta (e.g., *Chāndogya Upaniṣad* 6.2.1: \"In the beginning, this was Being alone, one only, without a second\"), it is not paralleled here. The corpus currently has no other Old Javanese *tattva* texts.",
